# JavaScript Study 01


##1.Data types

- Immutable data types: premitive types, frozen objects (i.e. object.freeze())

- Mutable data types: all objects by default are mutable in JS

- Favor immutable data type always for a few reasons: <br>

1) Security <br>

2) Thread Safety <br>

3) Reduce Human Mistakes <br>


##2.String Concatenation

```javascript

console.log('my' + ' cat');

console.log('1' + 2);

console.log('string literlas:



.....

1 + 2 = ${1 + 2}');

console.log("jay's \n\tbook"); // must use "" for \n or \t

```

##3.Increment and decrement operators

<strong>ex) +, -, /, *, **, %</strong>


```javascript

let counter = 2;

const preIncrement = ++counter;

// counter = counter + 1;

// preIncrement = counter;

console.log(`preIncrement: ${preIncrement}, counter: ${counter}`);

const postIncrement = counter ++;

// postIncrement = counter;

// counter = counter + 1;

console.log(`postIncrement: ${postIncrement}, counter: ${counter}`);

```

<strong>Result</strong> <br>

![image.png](data:image/png;base64,)


##4.Equality



```javascript

const stringFive = '5';

const numberFive = 5;



// == loose equality, with type conversion

console.log(stringFive == numberFive);

console.log(stringFive != numberFive);



// === strict equality, no type conversion

console.log(stringFive === numberFive);

console.log(stringFive !== numberFive);



//ex

console.log(0 == false); //T

console.log(0 === false); //F

console.log('' == false); //T

console.log('' === false); //F

console.log(null == undefined); //T

console.log(null === undefined); //F



// 8. Conditional operators: if

// if, else if, else

const name = 'df';

if (name  === 'jay'){

    console.log('Welcome Jay');

}else if(name === 'coder'){

    console.log('You are amazing coder')

}else{

    console.log('unknown');

}

```

##7.Switch Statement

```javascript

const browser = 'IE';

switch (browser) {

    case 'IE':

        console.log('go away!');

        break;

    case 'Chrome':

        break;

    case 'Firefox':

        break;

    default:

        console.log('same all');

        break;

}

```

<strong>Result</strong><br>

![Screenshot 2023-03-20 at 9.29.32 PM.png](data:image/png;base64,)


##8.Loops

- while, for, do while


```javascript

//while

let i = 3;

while (i > 0){

    console.log(`while: ${i}`);

    i--;

}



//do while

do{

    console.log(`do while: ${i}`);

    i--;

} while (i > 0);



//for

for(let i = 3; i > 0; i = i - 2){

    console.log(`inline variable for: ${i}`);

}

```

<strong>Result</strong><br/>

![Screenshot 2023-03-20 at 9.31.48 PM.png](data:image/png;base64,)


##9.Sample Questions

Q1: Iterate from 0 to 10 and print even numbers numbers (use continue) <br>

Q2: Iterate from 0 to 10 and print numbers until reaching 8 (use break)


<strong>Answers</strong>

```javascript

// Q1 with use continue

for (let i = 0; i <= 10; i++){

    if(i % 2 !== 0){

        continue;

    }

    console.log(`q1.${i}`);

}



// Q2: Iterate from 0 to 10 and print numbers until reaching 8 (use break)

for (let i = 0; i <= 10; i++){

    console.log(`i = ${i}`);

    if (i == 8){

        break;

    }

}



```
